--- PDF SUMMARY (Document was 37 pages long) ---
The document was too long to read directly, so here is a detailed summary of all sections:

In "A Business by Any Other Name: Firm Name Choice as a Signal of Firm Quality," Ryan C. McDevitt explores how a firm's name, particularly in the context of plumbing services, can signal its quality. The study finds that firms with names starting with "A" or a number receive more complaints and charge higher prices than others. Specifically, these "A" plumbing firms have five times more complaints, related to their choice to appear at the top of directory listings like the Yellow Pages. Despite common assumptions, increased complaints didn't correlate solely with higher business volume.

The study sets forth a model where market size affects information asymmetry. Larger markets tend to have more firms adopting "A" names and exhibit greater quality dispersion among these firms. This suggests low-quality firms use such names to attract less informed consumers who prefer quicker search processes.

Empirical findings support the model, with "A" firms showing a 8.4% price premium and more advertising in directories and online, correlating with higher complaint rates. These findings argue that costly advertisements do not necessarily indicate high quality, contrary to traditional signaling models like Milgrom and Roberts 1986, suggesting potential inefficiencies in position auctions within these markets.

Overall, McDevitt contributes to the understanding of naming as a market signal, highlighting the complex interplay between firm strategies, consumer search behavior, and market size in determining firm quality signals.

The technical paper investigates firm name choice and consumer search behavior using data on plumbing firms in Illinois sourced from ReferenceUSA and the Better Business Bureau (BBB). 

